The SeatBooking entity represents a many-to-many relationship between the Booking and Seat entities. This allows for flexibility in associating multiple seats with a booking and, conversely, multiple bookings for the same seat

ol.li: User logs in or registers with their username and password.( auth-service will be handling all register and auth related functionality, here user info will be stored in an RDBMS)
User selects the movie "Titanic" from the list of available movies.(req will be served by API server)
all theater and showtimes are shown to user( query the cache and on cache miss query the DB and show the aggregated showtimes as per user locations sorted by nearest to farthest).
User selects a showtime for "Titanic" at the chosen theater. The showtime specifies the date and time of the screening.
The system displays the layout of the theater's screen, showing the different seat types (e.g., Gold, Platinum, Standard) available in different sections.

User can view which seats are available (unbooked) and which seats are already booked by others. by querying seatStatus table like for select * from seat_status where show id 123 and status =='available' and mark rest all seats from the screen as booked/reserved, here in case of large chains like innox, pvr having their own IT system and DB, we will query their system to fetch this information via API.

User selects 2 seats of their choice, taking into account the seat types and their prices. Let's say the user selects one "Gold" seat and one "Standard" seat. at this time a booking id wil be generated and records will created in booking_seat table with all selected seats marked as reserved status for 10 min, also at this time seat_status table will be updated with reserved for that showtime, again here based on type of partner we can push the info to their IT system via API.
User reviews their booking, including the selected seats, showtime, and total price based on the seat types.
User proceeds to make the payment using their preferred payment method (e.g., credit card, debit card, online payment).

After successful payment, the system generates a booking confirmation with details like booking ID, showtime, seat numbers, and total price. and update status in booking_seat and seat__status to confirmed

for failure cases( like user closes the app, timeout happens or payment failure) timeout will happen and booking id and corresponding records from seat_booking table will be deleted and status in seat status table will be made avaiable for that showtime and all seat id's booked under that booking.
Enjoy the Movie

ol.li: separate partner integration module will be used to onboard both type of partners (with & without IT their own system)
both UI/API integration given to customer to onboard their theaters, screens and seating etc
partners can use this module to onboard new showtimes, movie info like thunbnails, trailer, cast & other metadata info

Partner integration module consists on inboud/outboud LB, and onboarding service and block servers etc for respective functions with each component being replicated across multiple AZ to fulfill high availabiltiy needs

trailers, thubnails and other video files would be processed by block servers(i.e chunking, encoding, compression) and then transcoded files would be put into s3 storage since these files are blob storage and object storage is what we need to store this type of data
since our application will be accessed across different locations same content could be pushed to CDN to reduce the latency based on the location of users.

ol.li: RDBMS i.e mysql is chosen since we have highly relational data and need strong ACID guaranty for transactions between diff entities like theater, screen, movie, showtime, booking , user etc
for ever increasing data like comments/review etc with frequent query patterns i chose no sql database like cassandra reasons being(scalabiltiy, performance)
for our caching, session management and rate-limiting needs, we have used an in memory DB redis, which is industry tested solution for such purposes.
for time taking I/O related operations like generating tickets and sending them via various channels (SMS/Email), we have used Async processing and Task/Messaging queues like rabbitMQ.
for centralized logging and monitoring we have used ELK stack, logstash will consume the loggings from rabbitMQ and send it to Kibana dashboard for monitoring
we have also used s3 object storage service to store video trailers related information
CDN cloudfront is being used to cache static content (images, css, html, js, video. audio) etc to reduce network latency across various geographies
to have highly available distributed system and to avoid Single point of failure(SOP) we will add redundancy at each layer(LB,API servers, caching, DB)
also we will move oldered data (>1 year) to cold storage via cron jobs or other cloud service to save cost on storage
k8s, docker, gitlab ci to be used for

ol.li: One of the key implementation is to avoid having duplicate booking i.e same seat for a showtime being booked by diff users

for this we will have a locking mechanism in place i.e once a users selects a seat it we will create a record in redis with a timeout callback event of 10 min and also update DB with seat status booked.
now there will be 3 cases ( payment suceess, payment failure, timeout)
for success case we will be updating the seat status as confirmed and deleting the record & so event callback from redis.
for failure case we will mark the seat as available again in DB and delete the event/record from redis
for timeout case event callback will be called and corresponding rollback status will be done in DB and partner API's etc and seat will be made available for others to book
now if 2 users simultaneously try to book same seat only one of them will succeed and other will be shown error page
